# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maui-dotnet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] It is thus enabling developers to create refactoring and diagnostics tools.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Two branches of official implementation are .NET Framework (closed-source, Windows-only) and .NET Core (open-source, cross-platform); they eventually converged into one open-source implementation: .NET 5.0.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] At .NET Framework 4.6, a new JIT compiler replaced the former.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The Unity game engine uses C# as its primary scripting language.
[src:maui-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:maui-dotnet/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML is used extensively in Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), Silverlight, Workflow Foundation (WF), Windows UI Library (WinUI), Universal Windows Platform (UWP), and .NET Multi-platform App UI (.NET MAUI).
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] In WPF and UWP, XAML is a user interface markup language to define UI elements, data binding, and events.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML elements map directly to Common Language Runtime (CLR) object instances, while XAML attributes map to CLR properties and events on those objects.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Anything that is created or implemented in XAML can be expressed using a more traditional .NET language, such as C# or Visual Basic .NET.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] However, a key aspect of the technology is the reduced complexity needed for tools to process XAML, because it is based on XML.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML originally stood for Extensible Avalon Markup Language, *Avalon* being the code-name for Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF).
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Before the end of .NET Framework 3.0 development, however, Microsoft adopted XAML for Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] In WPF, XAML describes visual user interfaces.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] WPF allows for the definition of both 2D and 3D objects, rotations, animations, and a variety of other effects and features.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] A XAML file can be compiled into a Binary Application Markup Language (BAML) file, which may be inserted as a resource into a .NET Framework assembly.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] At run-time, the framework engine extracts the BAML file from assembly resources, parses it, and creates a corresponding WPF visual tree or workflow.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] In WF contexts, XAML describes potentially long-running declarative logic, such as those created by process modeling tools and rules systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] The serialization format for workflows was previously called XOML, to differentiate it from UI markup use of XAML, but now they are no longer distinguished.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] However, the file extension for files containing the workflow markup is still ".xoml".
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML uses a specific way to define look and feel called *Template*s; differing from Cascading Style Sheet syntax, it is closer to XBL.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] To create XAML files, one could use Microsoft Expression Blend, Microsoft Visual Studio, the hostable WF visual designer, or XAMLPad.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] This Windows Presentation Foundation example shows the text "Hello, world!" in the top-level XAML container called Canvas.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] The schema (the `xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/..."` part) may have to be changed to work on some computers.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] A crucial part of utilizing XAML to its full potential is making appropriate usage of binding, as well as creating custom user elements as required.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] These versions have some differences in the parsing behavior.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Additionally, the Silverlight 4 XAML parser is not 100% backward-compatible with Silverlight 3 files.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Silverlight 3 XAML files may be rejected or parsed differently by the Silverlight 4 parser.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Besides Microsoft implementations, there is also OpenSilver (formerly known as CSHTML5), a contemporary web technology implementation.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Historically, XAML based applications could be run in some web browsers, such as Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] This could be achieved through XBAP files created from WPF applications, or via the Silverlight browser plugin.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] However, both these methods are now unsupported on all major browsers due to their reliance on the discontinued NPAPI browser plugin interface.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] In 2007, European Committee for Interoperable Systems (ECIS) – a coalition of mostly American software companies – accused Microsoft of attempting to hijack HTML and replace it with XAML, thus creating a vendor lock-in.
[src:maui-dotnet/extensible-application-markup-language] Jeremy Reimer, writing for *Ars Technica* described this comment as "the most egregious error" and added that XAML is unlikely to ever replace HTML.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] The mobile app development sector has experienced significant growth in Europe.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] A 2017 report from the Progressive Policy Institute estimated there were *1.89 million jobs* in the *app economy* across the European Union (EU) by January 2017, marking a 15% increase from the previous year.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] These jobs include roles such as mobile app developers and other positions supporting the app economy.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] To facilitate developing applications for mobile devices, and the consistency thereof, various approaches have been taken.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Most companies that ship a product (e.g., Apple, iPod/iPhone/iPad) provide an official software development kit (SDK).
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] They may also opt to provide some form of software testing and/or quality assurance (QA).
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] In exchange for being provided the SDK or other tools, it may be necessary for a prospective developer to sign some form of non-disclosure agreement (NDA), which restricts the sharing of privileged information.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] As part of the development process, mobile user interface (UI) design is an essential step in the creation of mobile apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Mobile UI designers consider constraints, contexts, screen space, input methods, and mobility as outlines for design.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Constraints in mobile UI design, which include the limited attention span of the user and form factors such as a mobile device's screen size for a user's hand(s).
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Mobile UI context includes signal cues from user activity, such as the location where or the time when the device is in use, that can be observed from user interactions within a mobile app.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Such context clues can be used to provide automatic suggestions when scheduling an appointment or activity or to filter a list of various services for the user.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] The user is often the focus of interaction with their device, and the interface entails components of both hardware and software.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] User input allows for the users to manipulate a system, and the device's output allows the system to indicate the effects of the users' manipulation.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Overall, mobile UI design's goal is mainly for an understandable, user-friendly interface.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Functionality is supported by mobile enterprise application platforms or integrated development environments (IDEs).
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Developers of mobile applications must also consider a large array of devices with different screen sizes, hardware specifications, and configurations because of intense competition in mobile hardware and changes within each of the platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Today, mobile apps are usually distributed via an official online outlet or marketplace (e.g., Apple: The App Store – Google: Google Play) and there is a formalized process by which developers submit their apps for approval and inclusion in those marketplaces.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Historically, however, that was not always the case.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Mobile UIs, or front-ends, rely on mobile back-ends to support access to enterprise systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] The mobile back-end facilitates data routing, security, authentication, authorization, working off-line, and service orchestration.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] This functionality is supported by a mix of middleware components, including mobile app servers, mobile backend as a service (MBaaS), and service-oriented architecture (SOA) infrastructure.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] The software development packages needed to develop, deploy, and manage mobile apps are made from many components and tools which allow a developer to write, test, and deploy applications for one or more target platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] First party tools include official SDKs published by, or on behalf of, the company responsible for the design of a given hardware platform (e.g., Apple, Google, etc.), and any third-party software that is officially supported for the purpose of developing mobile apps for that hardware.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] With bring your own device (BYOD) becoming the norm within more enterprises, IT departments often need stop-gap, tactical solutions that layer atop existing apps, phones, and platform component.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Many system-level components are needed to have a functioning platform for developing mobile apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Criteria for selecting a development platform usually include the target mobile platforms, existing infrastructure, and development skills.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] When targeting more than one platform with cross-platform development, it is also important to consider the impact of the tool on the user experience.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Performance is another important criterion, as research on mobile apps indicates a strong correlation between application performance and user satisfaction.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Along with performance and other criteria, the availability of the technology and the project's requirements may drive the development between native and cross-platform environments.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] To aid the choice between native and cross-platform environments, some guidelines and benchmarks have been published.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Typically, cross-platform environments are reusable across multiple platforms, leveraging a native container while using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for the user interface.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] In contrast, native environments are targeted at one platform for each of those environments.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] For example, Android development occurs in the Eclipse IDE using Android Developer Tools (ADT) plugins, Apple iOS development occurs using the Xcode IDE with Objective-C and/or Swift, Windows and BlackBerry each have their own development environments.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Mobile applications are first tested within the development environment using emulators and later subjected to field testing.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Emulators provide an inexpensive way to test applications on mobile phones to which developers may not have physical access.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] The following are examples of tools used for testing applications across the most popular mobile operating systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] According to a 2020 Industry Report on Applications, 46% of mobile app users have stated that they have stopped using or uninstalled an app due to poor performance.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Many patent applications are pending for new mobile phone apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/mobile-app-development] Most of these are in the technological fields of business methods, database management, data transfer, and operator interface.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:maui-dotnet/net-maui] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] With a C#-shared codebase, developers can use Xamarin tools to write native Android, iOS, and Windows apps with native user interfaces and share code across multiple platforms, including Windows, macOS, and Linux.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] According to Xamarin, over 1.4 million developers were using Xamarin's products in 120 countries around the world as of April 2017.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On February 24, 2016, Microsoft announced it had signed a definitive agreement to acquire Xamarin.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Microsoft ended support for Xamarin on May 1, 2024, in favor of .NET MAUI.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In 1999 Miguel de Icaza and Nat Friedman launched what eventually became known as Ximian to support and develop software for de Icaza's nascent GNOME project.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] After Microsoft first announced their .NET Framework in June 2000, de Icaza began investigating whether a Linux version was feasible.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] The Mono open source project was launched on July 19, 2001.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Ximian was bought by Novell on August 4, 2003, which was then acquired by Attachmate in April 2011.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] After the acquisition, Attachmate announced hundreds of layoffs for the Novell workforce, including Mono developers, putting the future of Mono in question.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On May 16, 2011, Miguel de Icaza announced on his blog that Mono would be developed and supported by **Xamarin**, a newly formed company that planned to release a new suite of mobile products.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] According to de Icaza, at least part of the original Mono team had moved to the new company.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] The name Xamarin comes from the name of the Tamarin monkey, replacing the leading T with an X.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] This is in line with the naming theme used ever since Ximian was started.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] After Xamarin was announced, the future of the project was questioned since MonoTouch and Mono for Android would now be in direct competition with the existing commercial offerings owned by Attachmate.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] It was not known at that time how Xamarin would prove they had not illegally used technologies previously developed when they were employed by Novell for the same work.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In July 2011, however, Novell – now a subsidiary of Attachmate – and Xamarin announced that Novell had granted a perpetual license to Xamarin for Mono, MonoTouch and Mono for Android, and Xamarin formally and legally took official stewardship of the project.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In May 2012, Xamarin released **XobotOS**, an experimental Android implementation using C# instead of Java.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In December 2012, Xamarin released Xamarin.Mac, a plugin for the existing MonoDevelop Integrated development environment (IDE), which allows developers to build C#-based applications for the Apple's macOS operating system and package them for publishing via the App Store.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In February 2013, Xamarin announced the release of Xamarin 2.0.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] The release included two main components: **Xamarin Studio**, a re-branding of its open-source IDE Monodevelop; and integration with Visual Studio, Microsoft's IDE for the .NET Framework, allowing Visual Studio to be used for creating applications for Android, iOS and Windows.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On July 17, 2013, Xamarin announced that they had closed $16 million (~$21.2 million in 2024) in Series B funding led by Lead Edge Capital.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Several investors from their Series A funding also participated, including Charles River Ventures, Floodgate, and Ignition Partners.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On August 21, 2014, Xamarin successfully closed an additional $54 million (~$70.3 million in 2024) in Series C funding, which is one of the largest rounds of funding ever raised by a mobile app development platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] As of August 2014 the total funding for the company was $82 million (~$107 million in 2024).
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On February 24, 2016, Xamarin and Microsoft announced that Microsoft signed a definitive agreement to acquire Xamarin.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Terms of the deal were not disclosed, though the Wall Street Journal reported the price at between $400 million and $500 million.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] At Microsoft Build 2016 Microsoft announced that they will open-source the Xamarin SDK and that they will bundle it as a free tool within Microsoft Visual Studio's integrated development environment, and Visual Studio Enterprise users would also get Xamarin's enterprise features free of charge.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] As a part of the acquisition they would also relicense Mono completely under the MIT License and would release all other Xamarin SDK software through the .NET Foundation also under the MIT License.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] The Xamarin company produces an open source software platform by the same name, and Xamarin 2.0 was released in February 2013.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin extends the .NET developer platform with tools and libraries specifically for building apps for Android, iOS, tvOS, watchOS, macOS, and Windows (UWP) primarily with C# in Visual Studio.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Developers can re-use their existing C# code, and share significant code across device platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Several well-known companies including 3M, AT&T, and HP have used the platform to create their apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin integrates with Visual Studio, Microsoft's IDE for the .NET Framework, and subsequently is available for use by macOS users through Visual Studio for Mac.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin also released a component store to integrate backend systems, 3rd party libraries, cloud services and UI controls directly into mobile apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Introduced in Xamarin 3 on May 28, 2014, and allows one to use portable controls subsets that are mapped to native controls of Android, iOS and Windows Phone.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Windows Phone was deprecated and removed in favour of UWP.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] It is also possible to target other different platforms such as Tizen (by Samsung), GTK (Linux), WPF and macOS even though they have stayed in Preview.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Microsoft has modified this framework to work with the Universal Windows Platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Microsoft enables native mobile development with Blazor.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Mobile Blazor Bindings allow developers to build native Android and iOS using C#, .NET, and web programming patterns.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] At Microsoft Build 2020, Microsoft announced that Xamarin.Forms was going to be merged into .NET 6 as .NET Multi-platform App UI (.NET MAUI).
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] NET MAUI adds macOS support via Mac Catalyst.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On May 23, 2022, during Microsoft Build 2022, .NET MAUI was released.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Microsoft stated that they will continue supporting Xamarin until it is fully replaced by .NET MAUI in May 2024.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin Test Cloud makes it possible to test mobile apps written in any language on real, non-jailbroken devices in the cloud.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin Test Cloud uses object-based UI testing to simulate real user interactions.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin is a .NET developer platform made up of tools, programming languages, and libraries for building many different types of applications.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin supplies add-ins to Microsoft Visual Studio that allows developers to build Android, iOS, and Windows apps within the IDE using code completion and IntelliSense.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin for Visual Studio also has extensions that provide support for the building, deploying, and debugging of apps on a simulator or a device.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In late 2013, Xamarin and Microsoft announced a partnership that included further technical integration and customer programs to make it possible for their joint developer bases to build for all mobile platforms.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In addition, Xamarin now includes support for Microsoft Portable Class Libraries and most C# 5.0 features such as async/await.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] CEO and co-founder of Xamarin, Nat Friedman, announced the alliance at the launch of Visual Studio 2013 in New York.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin is useful in developing iOS and Android apps.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On March 31, 2016, Microsoft announced that they were merging all of Xamarin's software with every version of Microsoft Visual Studio including Visual Studio Community, and this added various Xamarin features to come pre-installed in Visual Studio such as an iOS emulator.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In February 2013, Xamarin Studio was released as a standalone IDE based on the open source project MonoDevelop for mobile app development on Windows and macOS, as part of Xamarin 2.0.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In addition to a debugger, Xamarin Studio includes code completion in C#, an Android UI builder for creating user interfaces without XML, and integration with Xcode Interface Builder for iOS app design.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] On Windows Xamarin Studio is now deprecated in favor of Xamarin for Visual Studio.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In 2016, Microsoft discontinued Xamarin Studio with the release of Visual Studio for Mac.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin.Mac was created as a tool for Apple technology application development using the C# programming language.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin.Mac, as with Xamarin.iOS and Xamarin.Android, gives developers up to 90% of code reuse across Android, iOS and Windows.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin.Mac gives C# developers the ability to build fully native Cocoa apps for macOS and allows for native apps that can be put into the Mac App Store.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] Xamarin's .NET Mobility Scanner lets developers see how much of their .NET code can run on other operating systems, specifically Android, iOS, Windows Phone, and Windows Store.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] It is a free web-based service that uses Silverlight.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] RoboVM enables developers to build Java apps for iOS and Android with fully native UIs, native performances, and all Java apps have the complete access to the APIs of each developer platform.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] In April 2016 Microsoft announced that they would discontinue RoboVM and cease all subscriptions after April 30, 2017.
[src:maui-dotnet/xamarin] BugVM, a fork of RoboVM was created to maintain the free open source status.
